                            <comment id="32085" author="luke" created="Thu, 14 Feb 2008 23:44:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This isn&apos;t a bug. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The way it works is the ExceptionTranslationFilter causes an AuthenticationEntryPoint to be launched. This merely redirects to your login form JSP. Your login form JSP is using standard tag libraries, that are not part of Spring or Spring Security. The standard tag libraries need to be configured appropriately for i18n. The issues we have linked this issue to explain more details, and you can also review &lt;a href=&quot;http://java.sun.com/j2ee/1.4/docs/tutorial/doc/JSTL6.html#wp63721&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://java.sun.com/j2ee/1.4/docs/tutorial/doc/JSTL6.html#wp63721&lt;/a&gt; for further background. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To explain why your other JSPs are working, we suspect this is because they are being rendered as part of your Spring MVC or Spring Web Flow controller infrastructure (ie as views). In this case, the Spring i18n infrastructure has set the javax.servlet.jsp.jstl.fmt.localizationContext property for you. Because your login JSP is probably not passing through the Spring DispatcherServlet, this property has not been set, and you will need to do it manually. Basically your choices are to set it manually, write a filter to set it, make the login view rendered via your Spring controller infrastructure etc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We hope this helps.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="32113" author="nlevitt" created="Fri, 15 Feb 2008 04:32:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I understand that it&apos;s a special situation, but it still ought to work, if there&apos;s any way to do it. Otherwise people have to keep a separate set of translations or do the special magic you mentioned just for the login page. It should &quot;just work&quot;. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
